	abstract = {We present \${\textbackslash}it\{CosmoPower\}\$, a suite of neural cosmological power spectrum emulators providing orders-of-magnitude acceleration for parameter estimation from two-point statistics analyses of Large-Scale Structure (LSS) and Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) surveys. The emulators replace the computation of matter and CMB power spectra from Boltzmann codes; thus, they do not need to be re-trained for different choices of astrophysical nuisance parameters or redshift distributions. The matter power spectrum emulation error is less than \$0.4{\textbackslash}\%\$ in the wavenumber range \$k {\textbackslash}in [10{\textasciicircum}\{-5\}, 10] {\textbackslash}, {\textbackslash}mathrm\{Mpc\}{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$, for redshift \$z {\textbackslash}in [0, 5]\$. \${\textbackslash}it\{CosmoPower\}\$ emulates CMB temperature, polarisation and lensing potential power spectra in the \$5{\textbackslash}sigma\$ region of parameter space around the \${\textbackslash}it\{Planck\}\$ best fit values with an error \${\textbackslash}lesssim 10{\textbackslash}\%\$ of the expected shot noise for the forthcoming Simons Observatory. \${\textbackslash}it\{CosmoPower\}\$ is showcased on a joint cosmic shear and galaxy clustering analysis from the Kilo-Degree Survey, as well as on a Stage IV \${\textbackslash}it\{Euclid\}\$-like simulated cosmic shear analysis. For the CMB case, \${\textbackslash}it\{CosmoPower\}\$ is tested on a \${\textbackslash}it\{Planck\}\$ 2018 CMB temperature and polarisation analysis. The emulators always recover the fiducial cosmological constraints with differences in the posteriors smaller than sampling noise, while providing a speed-up factor up to \$O(10{\textasciicircum}4)\$ to the complete inference pipeline. This acceleration allows posterior distributions to be recovered in just a few seconds, as we demonstrate in the \${\textbackslash}it\{Planck\}\$ likelihood case. \${\textbackslash}it\{CosmoPower\}\$ is written entirely in Python, can be interfaced with all commonly used cosmological samplers and is publicly available at https://github.com/alessiospuriomancini/cosmopower .},
